22 Elias explained that time was not a straight line, but a loop — fragile, constantly wearing thin. The clocks in his shop weren’t just telling time — they were stitching it back together. And Model 103, the heart of the shop, had been failing. If it stopped entirely, people wouldn’t die — they’d forget. Whole histories, undone. People rewritten or erased. Reality would fold in places where the stitching came loose.
